item.title: The Evolution of IDE - Ultra ATA 66 Hard Drive Roundup
item.description: The Evolution of IDE The IDE or Integrated Drive Electronics interface was developed back in 1988 and was actually an attempt to consolidate all of the different non-SCSI drives at the time to a standard interface. Before that time, many manufacturers loosely followed the designs of CDC interfaces, but they often made proprietary changes that made compatibility difficult. The industry, knowing they needed a standardized interface, formed what is known as the Common Access Method Committee (CAMC), and formulated the specifications for the AT Attachment or ATA standard.
